  "prompt": "Can I keep savings account if my status changes to NRI? What happens to my PPF and NPS accounts?",
  "response": "Yes, you can retain a savings account in India if your status changes to Non-Resident Indian (NRI). However, you must inform your bank about your change in residency status, and depending on the bank's policy, your account may need to be converted to an NRI account, such as a Non-Resident External (NRE) account or a Non-Resident Ordinary (NRO) account.\n\nRegarding your Public Provident Fund (PPF) and National Pension System (NPS) accounts:\n\n1. **PPF Account**: Once you become an NRI, you cannot continue to make new contributions to your PPF account. However, you can keep the account until maturity, and it will continue to earn interest. The maturity amount can typically be withdrawn, or you can extend the account for an additional period if needed.\n\n2. **NPS Account**: As an NRI, you can continue to contribute to your NPS account. However, you will need to comply with the guidelines set by the Pension Fund Regulatory and Development Authority (PFRDA) regarding the contributions and withdrawals. It may have specific procedures for NRIs, so it's essential to check with your NPS fund manager.\n\nAlways consult with your bank or a financial advisor familiar with NRI regulations for personalized guidance based on your specific situation.",
